  "prompt": "What were the major events of Spain in 1492?",
  "response": "Spain experienced several major events in the year 1492 that were highly significant in its history:\n\n1. **The Alhambra Decree**: On March 31, 1492, King Ferdinand and Queen Isabella issued the Alhambra Decree (also known as the Edict of Expulsion), which ordered the expulsion of all Jews from Spain. Jews were given until July 31, 1492, to either convert to Christianity or leave the country. This decree was a pivotal event in Spanish history, leading to the forced migration and suffering of countless Jewish families.\n\n2. **The Conquest of Granada**: On January 2, 1492, the Catholic Monarchs Ferdinand and Isabella successfully conquered the Emirate of Granada, the last Muslim stronghold in Spain. The fall of Granada marked the end of the Reconquista, the centuries-long campaign by Christian kingdoms to reclaim Iberian territory from Muslim rulers. The conquest of Granada effectively unified Spain under Christian rule.\n\n3. **Christopher Columbus's Voyage**: On August 3, 1492, Christopher Columbus set sail from Palos de la Frontera on a voyage that would eventually lead to the discovery of the New World. Sponsored by Ferdinand and Isabella, Columbus embarked on his journey with the aim of finding a westward route to Asia. On October 12, 1492, he landed in the Bahamas, leading to the European discovery of the Americas and subsequent colonization.\n\nThese events had profound impacts on Spanish society, politics, and its position in world history, shaping the future of Spain as a powerful and influential nation.",
